Architecture Overview

Multi-component system: Electron desktop app, Node.js server, browser extensions, and Firebase backend.



1. Desktop Client (Electron Application)

Location: /client/

Technology Stack:

Electron v31.3.1 — Desktop app framework

TypeScript v5.6.3 — Type-safe JavaScript

Node.js — Runtime environment

Architecture:

Main Process (src/main.ts): Window management, IPC, system integration

Renderer Process (viewer.html + viewer.js): UI rendering

Preload Script (src/preload/preload.ts): Secure IPC bridge with contextIsolation: true

Security:

nodeIntegration: false

contextIsolation: true

IPC via contextBridge for secure communication

Build System:

TypeScript compiler (tsc)

Output: dist/ directory

Scripts: npm run build → npm run dev



2. Backend Server

Location: /server/

Technology Stack:

Node.js with Express v4.19.2

TypeScript v5.6.3

ES Modules ("type": "module")

Key Libraries:

cheerio — HTML parsing/metadata extraction

node-fetch — HTTP requests

robots-parser — robots.txt parsing

firebase-admin — Server-side Firebase operations

Functionality:

REST API (/api/v1/save-url)

Metadata extraction from URLs

Local HTTP server (port 3000)

Extension communication



3. Browser Extensions

Location: /browser-extension/

Supported Platforms:

Chromium (Chrome, Arc, Edge)

Firefox

Safari

Technology:

Vanilla JavaScript (no framework)

Browser Extension APIs

Content scripts for page interaction

Background scripts for shortcuts

Features:

Global keyboard shortcuts (Cmd+Shift+S)

Image hover detection

URL capture from active tab

Communication with Electron app via localhost



4. Backend Services (Firebase)

Technology:

Firebase v12.7.0 (Web SDK)

Firebase Admin SDK v13.6.0 (server-side)

Services Used:

Authentication: Google OAuth, Instagram OAuth

Firestore: Real-time database

Collections: users/{userId}/items, users/{userId}/directories, users/{userId}/instagramSession

Security Rules: Custom rules for user data isolation



5. Frontend (Renderer Process)

Technology:

Vanilla JavaScript (no React/Vue/Angular)

HTML5 + CSS3

Custom CSS variables for theming

UI Structure:

Single-window application

Sidebar layout (Dock + Content area)

Drag-and-drop functionality

Real-time Firestore listeners

Styling:

CSS custom properties (--border-default, --bg-primary, etc.)

Flexbox layouts

Responsive design



6. Development Tools & Configuration

TypeScript Configuration:

Target: ES2020

Module: CommonJS (client), ES Modules (server)

Strict mode enabled

Build Process:

TypeScript compilation (tsc)

Output to dist/ directory

Electron loads compiled JavaScript

Environment:

dotenv for environment variables

Firebase config from env vars with fallbacks



7. Communication Flow

Browser Extension → Local HTTP Server (port 3000) → Electron Main Process

                                                          ↓

Electron Main Process ↔ IPC ↔ Renderer Process ↔ Preload Script

                                                          ↓

Firebase (Firestore + Auth) ← Electron Main Process (Firebase SDK)



Key Communication:

IPC (Inter-Process Communication) between main and renderer

HTTP for extension-to-app communication

Firebase SDK for cloud services

Local HTTP servers for inter-process communication



8. Data Flow

User Action: Keyboard shortcut in browser

Extension: Captures URL/tab info

Server: Receives save request, extracts metadata

Electron: Saves to Firestore via Firebase SDK

Renderer: Real-time listener updates UI

Firestore: Stores data with user isolation



9. Security Features

Context Isolation: Renderer cannot access Node.js directly

Preload Bridge: Secure API exposure via contextBridge

Firestore Security Rules: User-based data access control

OAuth Authentication: Google/Instagram sign-in



Summary

Desktop: Electron + TypeScript

Server: Node.js + Express + TypeScript

Extensions: Vanilla JavaScript

Backend: Firebase (Auth + Firestore)

Frontend: Vanilla JavaScript + HTML/CSS

Build: TypeScript compiler

Communication: IPC, HTTP, Firebase SDK

This is a full-stack TypeScript application using Electron for desktop, Node.js for server, and Firebase for backend services, with browser extensions for cross-platform URL capture.



10. Sync/Async Process Parity (browser-extension/chromium)

When modifying hover detection, container extraction, or host-count logic:

- Visibility: Use isVisibleForHostCheck (containerExtractor) in BOTH Sync (countDiscoveryHostsIn) and Async (countDiscoveryHostsResolved). Never use a relaxed check in Async that could re-adopt containers rejected by Sync.

- Context inheritance: Async must inherit effectiveBranchMode (host/base_domain) and preResolved from Main-Process. In host mode, use preResolvedMain (not preResolvedBroad) for Late-expansion.

- Dual-process application: All logic updates (host filtering, intent detection, structural rules) must be applied to BOTH the Ascend Loop (Sync) and Late-Expansion/Purity Check (Async). Use shared utilities to prevent drift.

- Consistency audit: Set window.__blinkInconsistencyCheck = true to log [Inconsistency-Warning] when Async expands beyond Sync boundaries.